{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510941"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:35:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:35:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11662"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11662"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0.6,0.31,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4283"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79160"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4283","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4283"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11662"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64512"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"361"},{"type":"tags","id":"1406"},{"type":"tags","id":"1583"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6549"},{"type":"tags","id":"9738"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5760"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42640"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79160"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man presents with a four month history of a painless ulcer on his right foot (image). He mentioned that his feet are painful after walking 500m. There is no history of rest pain or fever. His medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus and chronic obstructive airways disease. He is a reformed smoker with a 30-pack-year history. On examination his right foot is pale, with a capillary refill time of 3 seconds. His femoral and popliteal pulses are palpable bilaterally, but the posterior tibial and dorsalis pedis pulses cannot be felt on the right leg. There is reduced sensation to light touch below the knees bilaterally. The ankle brachial index is 0.5 on the right leg, and 0.7 on the left leg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nerve conduction studies","Electromyography","Duplex ultrasonography","CT angiogram","MR angiography"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of diabetes-related foot ulceration due to peripheral neuropathy and peripheral arterial disease (PAD). His clinical findings, including the site of the ulcer, intermittent pain during exercise, cool temperature and reduced palpable pulses support the diagnosis of PAD. The lack of pain in the ulcer is almost diagnostic of peripheral neuropathy. His risk factors for PAD include smoking, diabetes, and hypertension. It is important to screen for neuropathy with a monofilament test to confirm the presence of neuropathy. Clinicians will also perform toes pressures as this is a more useful predictor of the likelihood of ulcer healing with good wound management. Chronic limb-threatening ischaemia is present when the foot perfusion is considered inadequate to heal the ulcer (almost certainly present in this case).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial investigations should include checking routine bloods (including eGFR), HbA1c and lipid profile. A foot X-ray is also important to exclude osteomyelitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are two important aspects to the management of PAD in this case. Firstly, after deciding that foot perfusion is inadequate, \u003Cstrong\u003Eduplex ultrasonography \u003C/strong\u003Eshould be done to assesses the anatomical location of the\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Earterial occlusive disease, which will need treatment to improve foot perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of peripheral arterial disease is also aimed at reducing the patient\u0027s risk of developing major cardiovascular events- such as stroke and myocardial ischaemia. Lipid lowering drugs, hypertensive medications, and antiplatelet therapy should be prescribed alongside smoking cessation and weight management. The HbA1c will guide whether adjustment to diabetes management is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiogram \u003C/strong\u003Eis usually performed as a second-line investigation after duplex ultrasonography, as pre-operative planning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENerve conduction studies\u003C/strong\u003E are not commonly used in this situation to diagnose peripheral neuropathy. The 10gram monofilament test is widely used by podiatrists to confirm sensory neuropathy. Vibration sensation may also be tested with a tuning fork.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectromyography\u003C/strong\u003E is not a useful investigation in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMR angiography\u003C/strong\u003E is another modality to diagnose PAD, however it is not the first-line investigation that is commonly used. This investigation may be indicated if osteomyelitis of the great toe is suspected and a plain X-ray is equivocal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Duplex ultrasound is the first-line investigation for peripheral arterial disease when intervention is indicated.","Peripheral arterial disease is a common complication in patients with diabetes and can lead to chronic limb-threatening ischaemia."],"references":["Hinchliffe RJ, Forsythe RO, Apelqvist J, Boyko EJ, Fitridge R, Hong JP, Katsanos K, Mills JL, Nikol S, Reekers J, Venermo M, Zierler RE, Schaper NC; International Working Group on the Diabetic Foot (IWGDF). Guidelines on diagnosis, prognosis, and management of peripheral artery disease in patients with foot ulcers and diabetes (IWGDF 2019 update). Diabetes Metab Res Rev. 2020 Mar;36 Suppl 1:e3276. doi: 10.1002/dmrr.3276. Epub 2020 Jan 20. PMID: 31958217. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31958217/","Aitken SJ. Peripheral artery disease in the lower limbs: The importance of secondary risk prevention for improved long-term prognosis. Aust J Gen Pract. 2020 May;49(5):239-244. doi: 10.31128/AJGP-11-19-5160. PMID: 32416650. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32416650/","Zubair A, Lotfollahzadeh S. Peripheral Arterial Duplex Assessment, Protocols, and Interpretation. 2023 Jul 20. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 35015455."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64512"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11662"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18454"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18454"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bb298216-3aaa-42c9-a2f6-e4bbc3cd4ce9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bb298216-3aaa-42c9-a2f6-e4bbc3cd4ce9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64512"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T15:51:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T15:51:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"